    <div class="section-num">A note from Merit Strategy</div>
    <h2 class="serif">What this <em>hub</em> is, and what it <em>isn't.</em></h2>

    <p class="lede">For the past nine months, Merit has worked alongside SAE to do the careful, often invisible work of preparing a one-hundred-and-twenty-year-old institution for its next chapter. Milestone 04 was not a redesign. It was the deliberate construction of the strategic and structural floor on which a future Workforce Development brand can stand.</p>

    <p>This document is the <em>value hub</em> for that work. It is the short-form companion to the full white paper — designed to travel across the organization, to be read in twenty minutes, to introduce the work to colleagues who weren't in the room. The long-form research and reasoning behind every recommendation lives in <em>The Mobility Workforce Imperative,</em> which this hub points to throughout.</p>

    <p>Three orientations may help the reader.</p>

    <p><strong style="color: var(--ink); font-weight: 600;">First, this report stands on the shoulders of M01 and M02.</strong> The brand and strategy work documented here — Phases 01 through 03 of Milestone 04 — was only possible because of the upstream foundation of Milestone 01's internal discovery and Milestone 02's audience research. M01 surfaced the institutional condition, the cliffs in the audience journey, and the strategic imperatives that defined the brief. M02 quantified the audience opportunity, defined the segments, and produced the personas that the strategy work was built around. M01 and M02 are not background; they are the structural foundation. M03's Program Architecture (V4) gave the brand work a portfolio to organize. The work in this hub belongs to all four milestones, not just the last one.</p>

    <p><strong style="color: var(--ink); font-weight: 600;">Second, the recommendations are interconnected.</strong> The brand architecture in Phase 01 only makes sense once you understand the audience research from M02. The strategy framework in Phase 02 only lands once you have the architecture. The future-state explorations in Phase 03 are tests of both. The hub is structured so each phase is self-contained, but the work is one body.</p>

    <p><strong style="color: var(--ink); font-weight: 600;">Third, this is foundation, not finish.</strong> The architecture is ready to implement. The strategy is articulated. The design exploration shows what becomes possible. Several of the most consequential next moves — applying the same Brand Map framework at the SAE parent level, building out brand governance, taxonomy and naming standards, closing the high-school program gap — remain ahead. The hub names them honestly.</p>

    <div class="signature">
