    <h3 class="serif">Six institutional <em>analogs.</em></h3>

    <p>The Hybrid Endorsed Branded House model is not unusual. Variants of it govern several of the most successful institutional brand systems in the world, each adapted to the conditions of its category. Six are useful as reference points for SAE.</p>

    <div class="three-col">
      <div class="col-feature">
        <h4>Apple.</h4>
        <p>Pure Branded House. Useful for new program naming — the &ldquo;SAE [Program Name]&rdquo; pattern at Tier 03.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-feature">
        <h4>Marriott Bonvoy.</h4>
        <p>Endorsed Brand portfolio with unified membership architecture across distinct sub-brands.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-feature">
        <h4>The Smithsonian.</h4>
        <p>The closest direct analog — institutional parent endorsing distinct museum identities.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="three-col">
      <div class="col-feature">
        <h4>Disney + Nat Geo.</h4>
        <p>Acquired-brand endorsement model. Useful for affiliate programs and external partnerships.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-feature">
        <h4>Harvard.</h4>
        <p>Parent institution with named professional schools — a model for parallel sub-brands under one parent.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-feature">
        <h4>The United Nations.</h4>
        <p>A multi-program institutional parent. The model for the breadth and ambition possible at scale.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="serif">Six governing <em>principles.</em></h3>

    <div class="sidebar">
      <div class="sidebar-label">Six Governing Principles · Brand Architecture</div>
      <p><strong>01 · The parent is always present.</strong> SAE International appears in every brand expression — as identity, endorsement, or framing.</p>
      <p><strong>02 · Legacy equity is preserved.</strong> AWIM and CDS retain distinct identities and visual systems, with consistent SAE endorsement.</p>
      <p><strong>03 · New programs are SAE-named.</strong> Every program developed from this point forward carries the SAE prefix as part of its proper name.</p>
      <p><strong>04 · Hierarchy is visible.</strong> The four-tier structure is legible to participants, partners, and staff within seconds of any encounter.</p>
      <p><strong>05 · Partnerships are co-branded with discipline.</strong> Industry-partner logos appear in defined patterns; partnership-driven naming does not override SAE primacy.</p>
      <p><strong>06 · Variants follow the parent.</strong> Within each program, variants follow consistent naming and visual patterns rather than spawning sub-identities.</p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="serif">Ready to <em>implement.</em></h3>

    <p>The architecture documented here is not a slide; it is a system. It is ready to be deployed across the institution as the operational rule for how SAE makes brand decisions. Implementation requires three things — none of them new strategy work, all of them tractable in the next phase of engagement.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong style="color: var(--ink);">A brand taxonomy.</strong> The translation of the architecture's principles into specific naming standards, visual hierarchy rules, and approved patterns for partnership branding. With worked examples for the most common decision categories.</li>
      <li><strong style="color: var(--ink);">A governance function.</strong> A small group of people, with defined authority, accountable for architecture integrity. Naming approvals, identity standards, communications hierarchy, partnership co-branding — all routed through a defined practice rather than negotiated case by case.</li>
      <li><strong style="color: var(--ink);">A migration plan.</strong> Sequenced transitions for existing programs that do not yet conform to the architecture. The AutoDrive audit in Phase 03 demonstrates the template at the program level; the institutional rollout would extend that template across the portfolio.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>None of this requires new research, new strategy, or new architecture work. It is implementation — and the architecture as articulated supports it as written. The next phase of partnership with SAE is the operationalization of what this phase made possible.</p>

    <div class="sidebar">
      <div class="sidebar-label">A note on the brand &amp; program inventory</div>
      <h4>The inventory is a <em>first pass.</em></h4>
      <p>Alongside the architecture itself, M04 produced a brand and program inventory — the catalog of program identities, marks, naming patterns, and communications surfaces that exist in SAE's current state. The inventory is intentionally a first pass, structured to evolve.</p>
      <p>It is designed to grow with the Program Architecture (V4) as the portfolio itself evolves: new programs get added as they are scoped; existing programs get updated as they are repositioned; cross-cutting initiatives get reclassified as the architecture's taxonomy is implemented. The inventory is a living document, not a finished asset.</p>
      <p>Treating it as living rather than fixed is operationally important: it means the architecture can be applied to new programs as they emerge, without waiting for a full inventory revision. The taxonomy work in the next phase is what gives the inventory its formal update cycle.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

