    <h2 class="serif">A primer: Merit's <em>Brand Map.</em></h2>
    <p class="section-deck">A framework for building a brand from the inside out. Belief, then strategy, then expression — in that order.</p>

    <p class="lede">Merit Strategy's brand work is structured by a proprietary framework called the Brand Map. The Brand Map is a sequenced articulation of what an organization believes, how it expresses those beliefs strategically, and how the audience encounters that expression in the world. It is not a logo project; it is not a tagline exercise. It is a system of meaning, behavior, and connection.</p>

    <p>The Brand Map distinguishes <strong style="color: var(--ink);">internal</strong> belief and strategy from <strong style="color: var(--ink);">external</strong> expression — and treats the flow between the two as the central work of building a brand. The framework moves left to right across three tiers: a Belief System (Purpose, Vision, Mission, Values); a Brand Strategy + Narrative layer (Stakeholders, Cultural Ideology, Architecture, Positioning, Promise, Narrative); and a Brand Expression / Touchpoints layer (Personality, Tone &amp; Voice, Messaging Mix, Identity System, Visual Metaphor, Stories). The pattern is intentional: <em>internal first, expression second.</em> A brand whose external expression precedes its belief system has, in the Brand Map's diagnosis, no foundation to express.</p>

