    <h3 class="serif">Parent DNA, sub-brand <em>voice.</em></h3>

    <p>One of the framework's most useful properties — and the one that matters most for SAE's specific brand condition — is that it scales <em>recursively.</em> The Brand Map can be applied at the parent level, governing the institution as a whole. The same Brand Map can then be applied at the sub-brand level — governing a sub-division like Workforce Development, or a program family like the Collegiate Design Series — without contradicting or duplicating the parent pass.</p>

    <p>The two passes are not parallel exercises that happen to use the same framework. They are <em>nested.</em> The parent-level Belief System and Brand Strategy flow into every sub-brand's strategy as <em>brand DNA</em> — the institutional substrate that gives every sub-brand its center of gravity. Each sub-brand then articulates its own Stakeholder model, its own Positioning, its own Promise, its own Narrative — because the audience it serves is specific, and the offer it makes is specific.</p>

    <div class="pullquote">
      <p class="pullquote-text">Same DNA, different voice. The parent passes its institutional substance to every sub-brand. Each sub-brand finds its own way to speak.</p>
      <div class="pullquote-attr">— Merit Brand Map · How parent and sub-brand relate</div>
    </div>

    <p>In practice this means: SAE International's Purpose, Vision, Mission, and Values — the parent Belief System — should be present, in operational substance if not in literal repetition, in every sub-brand's strategy. The Workforce Development Brand Strategy documented below is consistent with the parent SAE belief system as currently articulated; it does not contradict it; it does not freelance from it. At the same time, the Workforce Development sub-brand has its own Stakeholder model, its own Positioning, its own Promise, and its own Narrative.</p>

    <div class="sidebar">
      <div class="sidebar-label">A scope note · what M04 covered</div>
      <h4>This pass was at the <em>sub-brand</em> level, not the parent level.</h4>
      <p><strong>What this engagement covered.</strong> Milestone 04 produced a complete Brand Map pass for the Workforce Development sub-brand: Stakeholder model, Cultural Ideology, Positioning, Promise, Narrative, audience personas, and an initial Brand Expression direction. Within this scope, the work is comprehensive.</p>
      <p><strong>What remains.</strong> The same Brand Map framework can and should be applied at the SAE International parent level. That parent-level pass — articulating Purpose, Vision, Mission, Values, the parent Stakeholder model, the parent Positioning, the parent Promise, and the SAE Narrative — was outside the scope of the Workforce Development engagement and is the explicit subject of a future engagement.</p>
      <p><strong>Why it sequences cleanly.</strong> The architecture in §03 is ready for parent-level use today. The Brand Strategy in §04 is ready for Workforce Development implementation today. The parent-level Brand Strategy work — when commissioned — will sit underneath both, providing the SAE-wide DNA that this Workforce Development pass currently inherits implicitly.</p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="serif">The Brand Map applied to <em>Workforce Development.</em></h3>

    <p>The Workforce Development pass produced four strategic outputs, each grounded in the M01 and M02 research and each tested against the personas and audience segments the research identified.</p>

    <h4>Stakeholder model.</h4>

    <p>Two primary tiers and two secondary tiers. <strong style="color: var(--ink);">Primary:</strong> students and prospective participants (the four M02 segments — Hands-on Builders, Career-Focused Achievers, Impact Seekers, Community Connectors); industry partners (legacy mobility employers, next-generation mobility companies, foundations). <strong style="color: var(--ink);">Secondary:</strong> educators and administrators (P–12 teachers, post-secondary advisors, school-system decision-makers); volunteers, alumni, and existing SAE membership.</p>

    <h4>Two positioning statements.</h4>

    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="col-feature">
        <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom: 12px;">For the student</div>
        <p style="font-style: italic; font-family: 'Fraunces', serif; font-size: 16.5px; line-height: 1.55; color: var(--ink);">For students who want to build the future they live in, SAE Workforce Development is the place where curiosity becomes capability — through hands-on projects, real-world challenges, and a community of mentors and peers that grows with you from the classroom to the career.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-feature">
        <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom: 12px;">For the industry partner</div>
        <p style="font-style: italic; font-family: 'Fraunces', serif; font-size: 16.5px; line-height: 1.55; color: var(--ink);">For mobility companies and foundations facing a structural workforce shortage, SAE Workforce Development is the only system that builds the multi-skill, mission-aligned, industry-ready talent pipeline the next decade demands — at every stage from Pre-K through early career.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h4>The brand promise.</h4>

    <div class="pullquote">
      <p class="pullquote-text">Cultivating the next generation of mobility leaders.</p>
      <div class="pullquote-attr">— Brand Promise · SAE Workforce Development</div>
    </div>

    <p>Three pieces of work in eight words. <em>&ldquo;Cultivating&rdquo;</em> commits to a long horizon — not recruiting, not entertaining, but tending growth over time. <em>&ldquo;The next generation&rdquo;</em> commits to the audience and to a continuity that crosses age tiers. <em>&ldquo;Mobility leaders&rdquo;</em> commits to ambition — the people who emerge from these programs are not technicians or hobbyists but the leaders, broadly defined, of the mobility category.</p>

    <h4>The narrative.</h4>

    <p>The Brand Map distinguishes the Promise (single line, primarily internal) from the Narrative (longer-form articulation that invites audiences into the work). The Workforce Development narrative was developed against the M02 audience evidence; an excerpt:</p>

    <div class="pullquote">
      <p class="pullquote-text">Mobility is more than transportation. It is how a society moves itself, its goods, its ideas, and its possibilities. The next decade of mobility — autonomous, electrified, sustainable, accessible, intelligent — will be built by people who haven't yet thought of themselves as builders. SAE Workforce Development exists to find those people early, to give them the hands-on experiences that make their curiosity real, and to walk alongside them from a fifth-grade classroom to a first job, a first patent, a first leadership role. We are not preparing students for the workforce. We are cultivating the workforce that will define what mobility means.</p>
      <div class="pullquote-attr">— Excerpt · SAE Workforce Development brand narrative</div>
    </div>

    <p>The narrative does three things at once. It expands the cultural definition of mobility. It centers the participant — not the program, not the institution — as the protagonist. And it commits to continuity across the journey. All three are direct echoes of M02 audience research findings.</p>
