    <div class="section-num">§ 05 · Phase 03 · Future-state explorations</div>
    <h2 class="serif">Visible parent, flexible <em>programs.</em></h2>
    <p class="section-deck">A design strategy that lets SAE always show up clearly while giving every program enough creative room to feel like itself.</p>

    <p class="lede">The architecture and strategy work in Phases 01 and 02 are, in a sense, abstract. They specify a system; they do not, on their own, demonstrate what the system feels like in practice. The Future-State Explorations are that demonstration. They were designed to test the brand architecture and strategy against real program contexts — and to produce design artifacts concrete enough that internal teams, board members, and executive stakeholders could see, not just read about, what the next chapter of SAE Workforce Development could look like.</p>

    <h3 class="serif">Three design <em>objectives.</em></h3>

    <div class="three-col">
      <div class="col-feature">
        <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom: 12px; color: var(--gold);">Objective 01</div>
        <h4>Pattern.</h4>
        <p>A repeating visual signature that signals &ldquo;SAE Workforce Development&rdquo; before any logo is read. Patterns flex by program — but the system's grammar is shared.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-feature">
        <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom: 12px; color: var(--gold);">Objective 02</div>
        <h4>Color.</h4>
        <p>A core SAE-anchored palette plus program-specific accents. Each program gets one or two accent colors that mark it as distinct without breaking the family.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-feature">
        <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom: 12px; color: var(--gold);">Objective 03</div>
        <h4>Structure.</h4>
        <p>A consistent grid, type system, and layout logic that programs share. Structure is what makes the system feel like a system rather than a portfolio.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="serif">Two design <em>anchors.</em></h3>

    <p>The design system was tested against two program contexts: one new, one existing.</p>

    <p><strong style="color: var(--ink); font-weight: 600;">MotionLab · City Challenge</strong> is a new high-school program concept developed against the highest-priority gap in the Program Architecture. Teams of three to five high-schoolers receive a real-world city challenge — accessibility, last-mile delivery, emergency-response routing, climate resilience — and design, prototype, and present a mobility-system response. Intentionally interdisciplinary, intentionally social, with explicit narrative ladders into post-secondary CDS programs.</p>

