    <p><strong style="color: var(--ink); font-weight: 600;">The AutoDrive Challenge audit</strong> was the second anchor — applying the architecture and strategy to an existing program with substantial equity. The audit found that AutoDrive's current presentation was structurally inconsistent across surfaces; the &ldquo;after&rdquo; version applied the four-tier architecture and the three design objectives consistently, producing a program identity that reads as both clearly SAE and recognizably AutoDrive. The substance didn't change. The presentation became internally consistent and externally legible.</p>

    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="col-feature">
        <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom: 12px; color: var(--rose);">Before</div>
        <h4>Inconsistent surface, unclear hierarchy.</h4>
        <p>Program logo varied across surfaces. SAE's identity inconsistent in size, position, presence. Color, type, and grid systems differed across web, print, and event signage. Substance was strong; surface diluted the strength.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-feature">
        <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom: 12px; color: var(--gold);">After</div>
        <h4>Consistent system, clear hierarchy.</h4>
        <p>SAE identity at top hierarchy on every surface. AutoDrive receives a controlled accent palette plus a defined pattern signature. Type and grid system unified across surfaces. Same substance, legibly framed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="serif">What the future-state work <em>established.</em></h3>

    <p>The Phase 03 work is not a brand launch. It is a proof-of-concept demonstration of what the architecture and strategy enable — and a template for the migration of existing programs into the new system. Three things, taken together, are its operational outputs.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong style="color: var(--ink);">The system works.</strong> Tested against both a new program and an existing program with substantial equity, the architecture and strategy produced design results that felt consistent across the family while letting each program land for its specific audience.</li>
      <li><strong style="color: var(--ink);">The design objectives compress operational complexity.</strong> Three variables (Pattern, Color, Structure) covering the legitimate design variation across programs is enough constraint to be manageable and enough flexibility to be honest.</li>
      <li><strong style="color: var(--ink);">The migration path is concrete.</strong> The AutoDrive audit demonstrated, with a real program, what happens when the architecture is applied to an existing identity. The work is non-trivial — it is also tractable, sequence-able, and budget-able.</li>
    </ul>
